    <title>Combined summary - BIP proposal - patch to raise selfish mining threshold.</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T19:26:31.757604+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-November/003573.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Various email conversations and discussions on the Bitcoin mailing list have been taking place regarding the potential vulnerabilities and flaws in the Bitcoin protocol. In particular, a paper published in 2013 introduced a mining strategy called Selfish-Mine, which allows colluding miners to earn more than their mining power and potentially manipulate the decentralized currency. Proposed solutions to address these vulnerabilities have been put forward, such as raising the selfish mining threshold, but concerns have been raised about the potential harm to miners when all are honest, no new vulnerabilities being introduced, and complete backward compatibility.Ittay Eyal and Emin Gun Sirer proposed a Bitcoin Improvement Proposal to raise the threshold on Selfish Mining attacks by replacing the arbitrary choice among equal-length chains with explicit randomness controlled by the protocol. However, Peter Todd has expressed concerns about the proposal, stating that it could lead to larger mining pools withholding blocks to split the network. Jeff Garzik has also cautioned against immediately fixing bugs without proper research and analysis, emphasizing the complexity of Bitcoin and the need for significant testing before any changes are made.The email exchange also included information on November webinars for C, C++, and Fortran developers to accelerate application performance with scalable programming models. Alessandro Parisi raised concerns about bugs found in the Bitcoin protocol, while Jameson Lopp questioned the vulnerability of selfish mining attacks. Overall, the discussions highlight the importance of addressing potential flaws and vulnerabilities in Bitcoin quickly but with caution and thorough analysis.In 2013, Ittay submitted a BIP to raise the selfish mining threshold, but Gregory Maxwell pointed out that this solution introduced a vulnerability where large pools could withhold blocks instead of broadcasting them to create incentives. When such pools eventually revealed their mined block, 50% of the hashing power would switch, splitting the network and benefiting the attacker. Peter suggested analyzing a deterministic switching scheme to address this issue. The conversations emphasized the complexity of Bitcoin and the need for careful consideration when making any changes to the protocol.</summary>
